* Proposals

  Since the EngSB project is a very opened project (should finally also delivered to 
 the open-source many things are discussed in the public. Mostly ideas are discussed
 first in the mailinglist; but when the idea should be fixed in a more consistent way
 mostly a proposal is written. For the EngSB project this should be done in the proposals
 section. The {{{contribute/proposals.html}proposals document}} in the contribute section
 explains in further details what specific kind of proposals exist and according to
 which guidelines they should be written.
  
* Related Projects

  There are many projects which are more (or less) related to the EngSB. Some of
 them are only theoretical work but also some of them are completely own projects.
 Some of done are done for companies some for scientific works. Small projects
 are regularly handled simply on an own site within actual work. For full 
 (more complex) projects an own way have to be gone which is explained 
 {{{contribute/relatedProjects.html}here}}.

* Licensing and Copyright

  When contributing to an open source project, licensing is an important factor. Since
 the EngSB core application is delivered under the terms of the Apache License, Version
 2.0, we encourage using it for any contributed work. The Apache License ensures the 
 rights of contributers and the project's open source community while not hampering the
 use and distribution in commercial products. You may however decide to provide your
 work under different terms that satisfy license compatibility requirements.
 
* File Header
  
    Every source file should include a header containing copyright and license
   information. This can be realized using comment-notation in file types such as *.java,
   *.xml, *.apt, etc. Some files, e.g. those containing raw binary data, might not provide
   a special notation. In this case the copyright notice may be omitted, if the file
   is covered by the application's general documentation.
  
    This is a file header example taken from the EngSB core application. It can be found
   in any source file since its very beginning as open source project.

